-- Overseas Funds Buy Net 5.61 Billion Rupees of India Stocks Yesterday Trade
-- Paresh Jatakia
-- 2010-07-16T13:55:32Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-16/overseas-funds-buy-net-5-61-billion-rupees-of-india-stocks-yesterday-trade.html

          
          
             Overseas  funds  bought a net  5.61
billion rupees  ($120.1 million) of Indian equities yesterday,
raising total investments in stocks this year to 393.6 billion
rupees, according to the nationâ€™s market regulator.  
 Investors purchased 42.3 billion rupees of shares and sold
36.7 billion rupees, the Securities and Exchange Board of India
said on its website  today . They invested 105 billion rupees in
equities last month.  
 Foreigners sold a net 1.13 billion rupees of bonds, paring
their debt purchases this year to 355.8 billion rupees.  
 Inflows from overseas reached a record 834.2 billion rupees
in 2009, exceeding the high set two years ago in local currency
terms, as the biggest advance in 18 years lured foreign funds.
They sold a record 529.9 billion rupees of shares in 2008,
triggering a record annual decline.  
 Overseas funds have invested 3.53 trillion rupees in stocks
and 678.4 billion rupees in bonds since they were allowed into
the country in 1993.  
 The regulator provides data on shares bought and sold by
large investors, including trades in the primary and secondary
markets, with a delay of at least a day.  
